{"ts":"2026-05-22T21:06:47.968Z","author":"claude-code-agent","op":"create","patch":[{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/id","value":"pm-uer0"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/title","value":"Harden read-then-lock window uniformly across history-redact/restore/history-repair"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/description","value":"Surfaced by CodeRabbit review on PR #44 (history-repair). history-redact, restore, and history-repair all read the history stream + on-disk item and compute the rewrite/reconciliation BEFORE acquiring the per-item lock, then acquire the lock only around the atomic write. This leaves a small TOCTOU window where a concurrent mutation between read and lock could let the command write a rewrite computed against stale state. The atomic write + rollback protects file integrity, and concurrent same-item history rewrites are rare, so this is low severity. If addressed, do it uniformly across all three commands (acquire the lock before the initial read, or re-read+re-verify under the lock before writing) rather than diverging one command from its siblings."},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/type","value":"Chore"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/status","value":"open"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/priority","value":3},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/tags","value":["code-quality","concurrency","history","locking"]},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/created_at","value":"2026-05-22T21:06:47.968Z"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/updated_at","value":"2026-05-22T21:06:47.968Z"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/author","value":"claude-code-agent"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/parent","value":"pm-rnpb"}],"before_hash":"3cc22dff72be7b14824654a7a64ea62b04799939b2fee54c1b5f52ca60bf6df0","after_hash":"faacde033604676006f422597a3639d142d61b00f12df859ec69939d60fbf4c7","message":""}
